37
38 POST-CONVICTION RELIEF BASED ON DISCREDITED FORENSIC SCIENCE
39
40 SECTION 5. Section 6 of this 2026 Act is added to and made a part of ORS 138.510 to
41 138.680.
42 SECTION 6. (1) A person convicted of a crime may file a petition for post-conviction re-
43 lief if the conviction was based in whole or in part on scientific expert testimony, scientific
44 expert evidence or scientific expert opinion derived from the application of one or more of
45 the following discredited forensic science disciplines:
[6]

A-Eng. SB 1515
1 (a) Hair microscopy;
2 (b) Bite mark analysis or bite mark comparison; or
3 (c) Comparative bullet lead analysis.
4 (2) Notwithstanding ORS 138.530, in a post-conviction relief proceeding based on a petition
5 described in this section, the court shall grant relief if the petitioner proves, by a prepon-
6 derance of the evidence:
7 (a) That the petitioner’s conviction was based substantially on scientific expert testi-
8 mony, scientific expert evidence or scientific expert opinion that applied one or more of the
9 discredited forensic science disciplines described in subsection (1) of this section; and
10 (b)(A) If the petitioner was convicted at trial, that there is a reasonable probability that
11 had the scientific expert testimony, scientific expert evidence or scientific expert opinion
12 applying the discredited forensic science discipline not been admitted at trial, the outcome
13 of the trial would have been different; or
14 (B) If the petitioner was convicted after pleading guilty or no contest:
15 (i) That the scientific expert testimony, scientific expert evidence or scientific expert
16 opinion applying one or more of the discredited forensic science disciplines was known to the
17 petitioner at the time of entering the plea; and
18 (ii) That the scientific expert testimony, scientific expert evidence or scientific expert
19 opinion was a material factor in the petitioner’s decision to plead guilty or no contest.
20 (3) When making a determination under subsection (2) of this section, the court shall
21 follow the procedures described in ORS 138.620.
22 (4) If court finds that the petitioner has met the requirements of subsection (2) of this
23 section, the court shall grant appropriate relief under ORS 138.520.
24 (5) ORS 138.550 (3) and (4) do not apply to petitions for post-conviction relief described
25 in this section.
26 (6) A person may file a petition under this section notwithstanding the fact that:
27 (a) The person did not object to the admission of the scientific expert testimony, scien-
28 tific expert evidence or scientific expert opinion applying the discredited forensic science
29 discipline at trial or raise the issue on appeal, unless the trial occurred on or after the ef-
30 fective date of this 2026 Act;
31 (b) The person pleaded guilty or no contest to the conviction;
32 (c) Before or after the conviction, the person made a confession or admission; or
33 (d) The person has completed the sentence associated with the conviction.
34 (7) This section shall be liberally construed to promote justice and to correct wrongful
35 convictions based on discredited forensic science disciplines.
36 (8) This section may not be construed to permit challenges to convictions for which the
37 forensic scientific evidence introduced at trial was based on objective and validated compu-
38 tational methods that have replaced the subjective visual comparison techniques used in the
39 discredited forensic science disciplines described in subsection (1) of this section.
40 (9) As used in this section:
41 (a) “Bite mark analysis” means the diagnosis of an injury as a human bite mark.
42 (b)(A) “Bite mark comparison” means the use of dental records and impressions to
43 compare the bite marks left on a victim or object with the dentition of a known individual,
44 that involves the subjective analysis of the characteristics of the bite mark and the dental
45 profile to form an opinion as to whether the known individual created the bite mark and uses
[7]

A-Eng. SB 1515
1 odontological analysis.
2 (B) “Bite mark comparison” does not include using dental remains for identification of
3 a deceased individual or making an identification based on DNA analysis of any biological
4 material that may be present within or around a bite mark.
5 (c) “Comparative bullet lead analysis” means the forensic examination of the chemical
6 composition of bullet fragments found at a crime scene, that is performed to determine if
7 the concentration of all seven elements, in addition to lead, in the bullet lead from the crime
8 scene match the concentration of the same seven elements in the bullet lead found in the
9 possession of a suspect, and that is based on the assumption that a given quantity of lead
10 has a unique chemical signature.
11 (d) “DNA” means deoxyribonucleic acid.
12 (e)(A) “Hair microscopy” means the use of a microscope to analyze the physical charac-
13 teristics of a hair sample from an unknown source, including the sample’s color, shaft form,
14 texture, medullary pattern and scale structure, and to compare the sample with a hair
15 sample from a known individual, as the basis of scientific expert testimony, scientific expert
16 evidence or scientific expert opinion by applying probabilities to the inclusion of the known
17 individual as the source of the hair, and is limited to situations in which:
18 (i) The expert stated or implied that the hair sample from the unknown source could be
19 associated with a specific individual to the exclusion of all other individuals;
20 (ii) The expert assigned to the positive association a statistical weight or probability,
21 provided a likelihood that the hair sample from the unknown source originated from a par-
22 ticular source, or provided an opinion as to the likelihood or rareness of the positive associ-
23 ation that could lead a fact finder to believe that a valid statistical weight can be assigned
24 to microscopic hair comparison; or
25 (iii) The expert cited the number of microscopic hair comparisons performed by the ex-
26 pert or the expert’s laboratory, and the number of samples from different individuals that
27 could not be distinguished from one another after analysis, as a predictive value to bolster
28 the conclusion that a hair sample belongs to a specific individual.
29 (B) “Hair microscopy” does not include any analysis of hair that involves mitochondrial
30 or nuclear DNA testing.
31 (f) “Odontological analysis” includes the assessment of the shape, size, spacing and
32 alignment of teeth.
33 SECTION 7. ORS 138.510 is amended to read:
34 138.510. (1) Except as otherwise provided in ORS 138.540, any person convicted of a crime under
35 the laws of this state may file a petition for post-conviction relief pursuant to ORS 138.510 to
36 138.680.
37 (2) A petition for post-conviction relief may be filed by one person on behalf of another person
38 who has been convicted of aggravated murder and sentenced to death only if the person filing the
39 petition demonstrates by a preponderance of the evidence that:
40 (a) The person sentenced to death is unable to file a petition on the person’s own behalf due to
41 mental incapacity or because of a lack of access to the court; and
42 (b) The person filing the petition has a significant relationship with the person sentenced to
43 death and will act in the best interest of the person on whose behalf the petition is being filed.
44 (3) Except as provided in section 6 of this 2026 Act, a petition pursuant to ORS 138.510 to
45 138.680 must be filed within two years of the following, unless the court on hearing a subsequent
[8]

A-Eng. SB 1515
1 petition finds grounds for relief asserted which could not reasonably have been raised in the original
2 or amended petition:
3 (a) If no appeal is taken, the date the judgment or order on the conviction was entered in the
4 register.
5 (b) If an appeal is taken, the date the appeal is final in the Oregon appellate courts.
6 (c) If a petition for certiorari to the United States Supreme Court is filed, the later of:
7 (A) The date of denial of certiorari, if the petition is denied; or
8 (B) The date of entry of a final state court judgment following remand from the United States
9 Supreme Court.
10 (4) Except as provided in section 6 of this 2026 Act, a one-year filing period shall apply
11 retroactively to petitions filed by persons whose convictions and appeals became final before August
12 5, 1989, and any such petitions must be filed within one year after November 4, 1993. A person
13 whose post-conviction petition was dismissed prior to November 4, 1993, cannot file another post-
14 conviction petition involving the same case.
15 (5) The remedy created by ORS 138.510 to 138.680 is available to persons convicted before May
16 26, 1959.
17 [(6) In any post-conviction proceeding pending in the courts of this state on May 26, 1959, the
18 person seeking relief in such proceedings shall be allowed to amend the action and seek relief under
